    "one_line": "Rapidly expanding ISIS affiliate doubling annual size with 1,000-1,500 fighters, one of ISIS's most profitable branches ($2M+ annually), controls al-Karrar office coordinating African operations, emerging transnational threat with foreign fighter recruitment spanning Africa and Middle East.",
    "overview": "Islamic State–Somalia (ISIS-Somalia/IS-Somalia) is the most strategically significant ISIS affiliate in Africa and one of the group's most financially valuable branches. Formed October 22, 2015 by defectors from al-Qaeda-affiliated al-Shabaab led by Somali cleric Abd al-Qadir Mumin (born ~1950-1953), ISIS-Somalia pledged allegiance to ISIS central leadership and gained formal recognition as Wilayat Somalia (province) in 2018. The group operates primarily from the Golis Mountains and Al-Madow Mountains in the Bari region of Puntland (northeastern Somalia), controlling critical maritime zones along the Gulf of Aden and Indian Ocean. As of 2025, ISIS-Somalia has approximately 1,000-1,500 fighters (doubled from ~500-600 in 2023), with growing proportions of foreign fighters from Ethiopia, Tanzania, Kenya, Sudan, and the Middle East. Most significantly, ISIS-Somalia hosts the al-Karrar office—a secretive financial and operational coordination center led by Mumin that coordinates ISIS activities across central, eastern, and southern Africa, making it one of IS central's primary financial engines ($2M-6M+ annually from extortion/smuggling/kidnapping). Under successor leader Abdirahman Fahiye Isse (appointed ~2023), ISIS-Somalia has demonstrated unprecedented military sophistication: December 2024 attacks killed 20+ Puntland soldiers using coordinated VBIEDs/suicide bombers, May 2024 shooting at Israeli embassy in Sweden, ongoing international recruitment campaigns targeting diaspora communities. With Abd al-Qadir Mumin increasingly recognized as de facto global ISIS leader (replacing Arab tribal-lineage requirement with Somali governance), ISIS-Somalia represents a critical transnational threat to US homeland security, regional stability, and global IS expansion strategy.",
